summary:
Rwanda-backed rebels overran Congolese troops and entered Goma after gunfire and shelling, displacing one million people who now shelter in the city. Rebels seized the aid hub in eastern Congo. The U.N. warns of a humanitarian crisis and risks further regional instability.

In Gaza, Israel permits displaced Palestinians to return to northern areas after a hostage release deadlock breaks; thousands affected by prior evacuation orders crossed back. This eases the enclave's division amid the ongoing war. Separately in the Gulf, Kuwait accuses Iran and proxies of a Thursday drone strike; Iran rejects the claim, amid regional tensions. US Vice President Vance travels to Pakistan for talks to stabilize the two-week U.S.-Iran ceasefire, which Pakistan helped broker; Netanyahu authorizes related Washington talks with Lebanon. These developments affect global oil flows through the Strait of Hormuz.

NATO launches its first coordinated response to suspected Baltic Sea cable sabotage after another deep-sea cable was severed, deploying assets to protect transatlantic communications. In China, Xi Jinping met Kuomintang chair Cheng Li-wun for the first time in a decade and expressed confidence in cross-strait unification; this affects Taiwan politics and U.S.-China ties ahead of a potential Xi-Trump summit. In space news, Artemis II's four crew members approach Earth re-entry for a Friday Pacific splashdown off California after the first crewed Moon mission in over 50 years; success advances NASA's lunar and Mars plans. SpaceX's Falcon 9 launched Crew-10 from Florida at 7:03 p.m. Friday with two NASA, one Japanese, and one Russian astronaut; it will dock Saturday to return stranded NASA astronauts Wilmore and Williams after nine months on the ISS."}
